Construct a basis of a `PiTensorProduct` of modules given bases of the modules, and relationship between the dual of a `PiTensorProduct` and the `PiTensorProduct` of the duals.

Main results:
* `Basis.piTensorProduct` (in `LinearAlgebra/TensorProductBasis.lean`): Let `Î¹` be a `Fintype` and `M` be a family of modules indexed by `Î¹`. If `b i : Îº i â†’ M i` is a basis for every `i` in `Î¹`, then `fun (p : Î  i, Îº i) â†¦ â¨‚â‚œ[R] i, b i (p i)` is a basis of `â¨‚[R] i, M i`.
* `PiTensorProduct.dualDistrib` (in `LinearAlgebra/Dual.lean`): The canonical linear map from `â¨‚[R] i, Dual R (M i)` to `Dual R (â¨‚[R] i, M i)`, sending `â¨‚â‚œ[R] i, f i` to the composition of `PiTensorProduct.map f` with the linear equivalence `â¨‚[R] i, R â†’â‚— R` given by multiplication.
* `PiTensorProduct.dualDistribEquiv` (also in `LinearAlgebra/Dual.lean`): A linear equivalence between `â¨‚[R] i, Dual R (M i)` and `Dual R (â¨‚[R] i, M i)` when all `M i` are finite free modules. If `f : (i : Î¹) â†’ Dual R (M i)`, then this equivalence sends `â¨‚â‚œ[R] i, f i` to the composition of `PiTensorProduct.map f` with the natural isomorphism `â¨‚[R] i, R â‰ƒ R` given by multiplication.
